structure:Agency.structure:Name: SDMX
structure:Agency.structure:Description: SDMX is an initiative to foster standards for the exchange of statistical information. It is sponsored by the Bank for International Settlements (BIS), the European Central Bank (ECB), the Statistical Office of the European Union (Eurostat), the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the Organization for Economic Co-Operation and Development (OECD), the United Nations (UN) and the World Bank.

structure:Agency.structure:Name: International Monetary Fund (IMF)
structure:Agency.structure:Description: The IMF works to foster global growth and economic stability. It provides policy advice and financing to members in economic difficulties and also works with developing nations to help them achieve macroeconomic stability and reduce poverty.

structure:Agency.structure:Name: Statistical Office of the European Union (Eurostat)
structure:Agency.structure:Description: Eurostat is the statistical office of the European Union situated in Luxembourg. Its task is to provide the European Union with high quality statistics at European level that enable comparisons between countries and regions. Website: http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/.

structure:Agency.structure:Name: UNESCO Institute for Statistics (UIS)
structure:Agency.structure:Description: The UNESCO Institute for Statistics (UIS) is the statistical office of the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO). The Institute produces the data and methodologies to monitor trends at national and international levels. It delivers comparative data for countries at all stages of development to provide a global perspective on education, science and technology, culture, and communication. The UIS is the official source for the indicators needed to achieve SDG 4–Education 2030 and key targets in science and innovation, culture and communication.

structure:Agency.structure:Name: Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD)
structure:Agency.structure:Description:
The mission of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) is to promote policies that will improve the economic and social well-being of people around the world.
The OECD provides a forum in which governments can work together to share experiences and seek solutions to common problems. We work with governments to understand what drives economic, social and environmental change. We measure productivity and global flows of trade and investment. We analyse and compare data to predict future trends. We set international standards on a wide range of things, from agriculture and tax to the safety of chemicals.
We look, too, at issues that directly affect the lives of ordinary people, like how much they pay in taxes and social security, and how much leisure time they can take. We compare how different countries’ school systems are readying their young people for modern life, and how different countries’ pension systems will look after their citizens in old age.
Drawing on facts and real-life experience, we recommend policies designed to make the lives of ordinary people better. We work with business, through the Business and Industry Advisory Committee to the OECD, and with labour, through the Trade Union Advisory Committee. We have active contacts as well with other civil society organisations. The common thread of our work is a shared commitment to market economies backed by democratic institutions and focused on the wellbeing of all citizens. Along the way, we also set out to make life harder for the terrorists, tax dodgers, crooked businessmen and others whose actions undermine a fair and open society.

structure:Agency.structure:Name: Metadata Technology
structure:Agency.structure:Description: Provider of consultancy, software, and services to the SDMX community.

structure:Agency.structure:Name: International Labour Organization
structure:Agency.structure:Description:
The ILO was founded in 1919, in the wake of a destructive war, to pursue a vision based on the premise that universal, lasting peace can be established only if it is based on social justice. The ILO became the first specialized agency of the UN in 1946.
The main aims of the ILO are to promote rights at work, encourage decent employment opportunities, enhance social protection and strengthen dialogue on work-related issues.

structure:Agency.structure:Description: The Bank of Israel is the central bank of the State of Israel. The main objectives of the Bank are listed and prioritized in the Bank of Israel Law : To maintain price stability; to support other objectives of the Government's economic policy, especially growth, employment, and reducing social gaps; and supporting the stability of the financial system.

structure:CodeList.structure:Name: Decimals
structure:CodeList.structure:Description: This code list provides a list of values showing the number of decimal digits used in the data. This code list was released in 2009. More information about this code list and SDMX code lists in general (e.g. list of generic codes for expressing general concepts like "Total", "Unknown", etc.; syntaxes for the creation of further codes; general guidelines for the creation of SDMX code lists) can be found at this address: https://sdmx.org/?page_id=4345.

structure:CodeList.structure:Name: Frequency
structure:CodeList.structure:Description: This code list provides a set of values indicating the "frequency" of the data (e.g. weekly, monthly, quarterly). The concept “frequency” may refer to various stages in the production process, e.g. data collection or data dissemination. For example, a time series could be disseminated at annual frequency but the underlying data are compiled monthly. The code list is applicable for all different uses of "frequency". This code list was formally adopted on 4 December 2013. More information about and supporting material for this code list and SDMX code lists in general (e.g. list of generic codes for expressing general concepts like "Total", "Unknown", etc.; syntaxes for the creation of further codes; general guidelines for the creation of SDMX code lists) can be found at this address: https://sdmx.org/?page_id=4345.

structure:CodeList.structure:Name: Sex
structure:CodeList.structure:Description: This code list provides coded information about the state of being male or female. This concept is applied if data needs to be categorised by sex. It applies not only to human beings but also to animals and other living organisms.

structure:CodeList.structure:Name: Unit Multiplier
structure:CodeList.structure:Description: This code list provides code values for indicating the magnitude in the units of measurement. More information about this code list and SDMX code lists in general (e.g. list of generic codes for expressing general concepts like "Total", "Unknown", etc.; syntaxes for the creation of further codes; general guidelines for the creation of SDMX code lists) can be found at this address: https://sdmx.org/?page_id=4345.

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Education type
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Determines whether education programmes cover formal initial and/or formal adult education

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Education level
structure:Concept.structure:Description: An ordered set which groups and classifies education programmes according to the knowledge, skills, competencies and qualifications which they are designed to impart

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Fields of education
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Fields of education based on ISCED 2013

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Grade
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Indicates the specific stage, class or year of instruction within the ISCED level in initial education

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Intensity
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Intensity of participation

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Country of origin
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Country of origin of statistical units

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Mobility
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Measures transfers between education systems (such transfers include the physical crossing of a border)

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Statistical unit
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Entity for which information is sought and for which statistics are ultimately compiled

structure:Concept.structure:Name: TIME_PERIOD
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Timespan or point in time to which the observation actually refers

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Observation value
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Value of a particular variable

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Frequency of observation
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Time interval at which observations occur over a given time period

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Reference area
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Country or geographic area to which the measured statistical phenomenon relates

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Reference institutional sector
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Reference institutional sector

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Counterpart institutional sector
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Counterpart institutional sector

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Expenditure type
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Specifies the type of expenditure data whether direct, transfers, etc

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Sex
structure:Concept.structure:Description: State of being male or female

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Age
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Length of time that an entity has lived or existed

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Unit of measure
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Unit in which the data values are expressed

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Table identifier
structure:Concept.structure:Description: List of current data collection tables

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Reference date for ages
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Reference date for ages

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Origin criterion
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Criterion used for country of origin

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Reference year start
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Start of the reference period. For example, start of school year or financial year

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Reference year end
structure:Concept.structure:Description: End of reference period. For example, end of school year or financial year

structure:Concept.structure:Name: School year start for FIN-STUD
structure:Concept.structure:Description: School year start for FIN-STUD (YYYY-MM-DD)

structure:Concept.structure:Name: School year end for FIN-STUD
structure:Concept.structure:Description: School year end for FIN-STUD (YYYY-MM-DD)

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Type of expenditure reported
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Specifies whether the expenditure reported is actual or budget expenditure

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Observation status
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Information on the quality of a value or an unusual or missing value

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Confidentiality status
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Information about the confidentiality status of the object to which this attribute is attached

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Observation comment
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Comments to the observation value

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Decimals
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Number of digits of an observation to the right of a decimal point

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Time period collection
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Dates or periods during which the observations have been collected for the target reference period

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Compiling agency
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Organisation collecting and/or elaborating the data being reported

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Unit multiplier
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Exponent in base 10 used for calculating the actual value in the unit of measure

structure:Concept.structure:Name: Breakdown group
structure:Concept.structure:Description: Group of dimensions by which the data are decomposed
